    <!-- ABOUT -->
    <section id="about" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <div class="section-kicker">About the System</div>
          <div class="section-title">
            A Multi-Year Research Project, Not a Weekend Indicator Pack.
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="section-desc">
          PROJECT_NAME started as a private research pipeline focused on FX and
          metals: understanding how different market regimes behave and how
          machine learning can forecast directional edge while respecting risk.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="badge-inline">Principle 01</span>
          <h3>Predictive Modelling &gt; Reactive Signals</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            Signals are generated by a neural model trained on multi-year
            historical data with walk-forward validation — not just a stack of
            moving averages. The goal is to estimate edge, not simply react to
            price.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="badge-inline">Principle 02</span>
          <h3>Regime Awareness</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            Trending, compressing, and volatile environments behave
            differently. A dedicated regime model classifies these environments
            and conditions when and how signals are allowed to fire.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="badge-inline">Principle 03</span>
          <h3>Non-Negotiable Risk Rules</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            Every signal respects ATR-based stops, controlled risk–reward
            ratios, and policy-layer thresholds calibrated via large-scale
            hyperparameter optimization. No martingale, no averaging down.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- METHODOLOGY / HOW IT WORKS -->
    <section id="methodology" class="section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <div class="section-kicker">Methodology</div>
          <div class="section-title">How PROJECT_NAME Generates Signals.</div>
        </div>
        <p class="section-desc">
          From raw data to live signal, the pipeline is fully systematic and
          repeatable. Below is a simplified view of the workflow used to
          produce trade ideas.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-4">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>01 — Data & Features</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            Ingests multi-timeframe OHLCV data (e.g., 15m, 60m, 240m) and
            constructs a curated feature set that captures volatility,
            momentum shifts, liquidity windows, extension filters, and custom
            indicators.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>02 — Neural Forecasts</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            A PyTorch-based NeuralSignalModel estimates directional edge.
            Hyperparameters are tuned with Optuna across hundreds of trials
            with strict train/validation splits and out-of-sample testing.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>03 — Regime & Policy</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            A regime model classifies trend/compression/expansion states. A
            policy layer applies thresholds, persistence rules, and volatility
            filters to decide whether a trade is allowed.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>04 — Signal Release</h3>
          <p class="muted">
            Once a setup passes all filters, the system generates a signal
            with entry, stop, target(s), and optional confidence metrics —
            then automatically publishes it via Telegram.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- TRANSPARENCY -->
